Ahli PPBM didakwa hina Majlis Raja-Raja
Zahid AF tampil dengan Radio Online Raku
AWANI 7:45 malam ini: Segelintir bekas pemimpin ibarat orang 'gila talak' - TPM
Segelintir bekas pemimpin ibarat orang 'gila talak' - Zahid
Tag: kerajaan, Idris Haron, Melaka, DUN
KENINGAU: The Oath Stone erected to guarantee the rights of Sabah natives in the federation of Malaysia is set to get a new and permanent home.
The Oath Stone or Batu Sumpah, originally placed in front of the Keningau district office that courted controversy when the key words Kerajaan Malaysia Jamin were taken away, is now set to be restored with its original words.
Tourism and Culture Minister Datuk Seri Nazri Aziz said the Oath Stone bearing the words Kerajaan Malaysia Jamin (The Government of Malaysia Guarantees) will be relocated to state land near the Heritage Museum here.
He said this followed the RM1.025mil approved by the Federal Government to fund the Oath Stones relocation.
The allocation is for the relocation of the Batu Sumpah, construction of new roads, a historical wall, softscape, Oath Stone plaque and parking lots, he said.
Nazri said of the amount, RM25,000 will be given to Huguan Siou or Kadazandusun paramount chief Tan Sri Joseph Pairin Kitingan, who is also the Deputy Chief Minister, for the ritual of relocation according to native customs in Keningau.
The whole process will be properly documented, Nazri said, adding that the relocation is under the 11th Malaysia Plan.
Controversy arose over the Oath Stone some two years ago when it was realised that the words Kerajaan Malaysia Jamin were missing from the plaque.
It remains a mystery as to where and when the original was changed but Bingkor assemblyman Datuk Dr Jeffrey Kitingan had given the government a plaque which he claimed to be the original. It has been handed over to the museum for safekeeping.
Meanwhile, Nazri said the Oath Stone will be placed at a location befitting its status and accessible to visitors.
The Oath Stone, he said, is an important historical heritage not only to Keningau and Sabah but also the federation of Malaysia.
The ministry is aware of the significance of this Oath Stone and its restoration and relocation work, he added.
He also said the ownership and management of the stone will still be under the Sabah government.
Nazri said the Oath Stone will be gazetted under the Cultural Heritage Enactment (Conservation 1997) once it has been moved.
The Batu Sumpah or Oath Stone was erected in the interior of Keningau on Aug 31, 1964, during a ceremony witnessed by federal and state leaders.
It serves to assure Sabahans that their rights to religious freedom, land, culture and customs are guaranteed.
